  "definitions": [
    {
      "definition": "A myeloid disorder that occurs in childhood and is characterized by persistent cytopenia, dysplastic changes in at least two hematopoietic lineages or in 10% or more of cells in one hematopoietic lineage, less than 5% blasts in bone marrow, and less than 2% blasts in peripheral blood, absence of bone marrow fibrosis, and absence of history of prior cytotoxic chemotherapy or radiation therapy. In a subset of cases, somatic mutations or cytogenetic abnormalities can be identified. Other cases are the result of pre-existing disorders with germline mutations, including Fanconi anemia, Shwachman-Diamond syndrome, and dyskeratosis congenita.",
      "type": "DEFINITION",
      "source": "NCI"
    },
    {
      "definition": "The most common subtype of the myelodysplastic syndromes affecting children. It is characterized by persistent cytopenia with less than 5% blasts in the bone marrow and less than 2% blasts in the peripheral blood. Most cases are associated with a normal karyotype, however, when abnormal, monosomy 7 is the most frequently seen cytogenetic abnormality.",
      "type": "ALT_DEFINITION",
      "source": "NICHD"
    }
  ],
